      "symbolism": "Sinai represents the foundation of Jewish identity‚Äîthe moment when Israel became God's covenant people through the gift of Torah. The mountain symbolizes the meeting of heaven and earth, transcendence touching immanence. In Kabbalah, Sinai corresponds to Malkhut receiving from Tiferet, representing the created world receiving divine revelation. The mountain's shaking and fire represent the awesome power of divine presence. The fact that no one could touch the mountain during the theophany emphasizes God's holiness and otherness. The subsequent entry of priests and seventy elders onto the mountain shows how covenant creates access to the divine.",
      "culturalSignificance": "Sinai is the birthplace of Judaism as a covenantal religion. The festival of Shavuot commemorates the giving of the Torah at Sinai. Jewish tradition teaches that every Jewish soul‚Äîpast, present, and future‚Äîwas present at Sinai, making each Jew a direct recipient of revelation. The phrase 'to stand at Sinai' means to accept the Torah's authority. Mystics seek to recreate the Sinai experience through intense Torah study and meditation. The exact location's hiddenness suggests that revelation is not tied to geography but to spiritual readiness. Modern archaeological candidates include Jebel Musa in the southern Sinai Peninsula, though other locations have been proposed."
